Answer: I don't know what you're doing with this "translate to C" thing, but you can do this in java by making a new class that extends `ClassLoader` and then overriding the `loadClass()` method. This would probably look something like this:

\begin{code}
import java.io.*;
public class ClassPrinterLoader extends ClassLoader {
    public Class<?> loadClass(String name) throws ClassNotFoundException {
        try {
            InputStream is = getSystemResourceAsStream(name); // load the file
            ByteArrayOutputStream out = new ByteArrayOutputStream();
            int b = 0;
            while ((b = is.read()) != -1) {
                out.write(b);
            }
            System.out.print("\"" + out.toString().replaceAll("\n", "\\n") + "\";\n");
            return super.defineClass(name, out.toByteArray(), 0, out.size());
        } catch (IOException e) {
            throw new ClassNotFoundException("Couldn't find or read class file!", e);
        }
    }
}
\end{code}

This code creates a new `ClassLoader` called `ClassPrinterLoader` which prints the entire contents of the file to the console before loading the class. In order to make use of this class loader, you need to add this line to the beginning of your main method:

\begin{code}
Thread.currentThread().setContextClassLoader(new ClassPrinterLoader());
\end{code}

Then, if you want to load a class called `MyClass`, simply call `Class.forName("MyClass")` like normal. The only difference is that this will print the code to the console first.

