Answer: As long as you have a compilable program, you can use any compiler that produces a binary file which outputs your string to stdout. To create such a binary from C++, see [this SO post](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/25798641/writing-a-binary-file-in-c).

If that doesn't work for you, here's a simple example. Assuming you're on a linux machine and have `bash` installed, you could put this in a file called `compile.sh`:

\begin{code}
#!/bin/bash

echo "#include <iostream>" >> tmp.cpp
echo "int main(){" >> tmp.cpp
echo "std::cout << \"hello world\" << std::endl;" >> tmp.cpp
echo "}" >> tmp.cpp
g++ -o tmp tmp.cpp
rm tmp.cpp
\end{code}

Make the script executable (`chmod +x compile.sh`) and then run `./compile.sh`. You should now have an executable called `tmp` in your directory, which outputs `"hello world"` when you run it.

