Answer: The error was that you used spaces instead of tabs to indent your code.

\strong{Wrong:}

\begin{code}
my_dict = {1:'A', 2:'B', 3:'C'}
    for x, y in my_dict.items():
        print(x)
\end{code}

\strong{Right:}

\begin{code}
my_dict = {1:'A', 2:'B', 3:'C'}
for x, y in my_dict.items():
    print(x)
\end{code}

It's always good practice to use tabs for indentation in python, because if you use both tabs and spaces together, then interpreter will throw an error.

\end{code}

Answer: You need to indent your `for` loop with one tab and your `print()` statement with two tabs. Also, `.items()` doesn't work in JavaScript, so you must use `Object.entries()`. See below:

\begin{code}
var my_dict = {
  1: 'A',
  2: 'B',
  3: 'C'
}
for (var [x, y] of Object.entries(my_dict)) {
  console.log(x);
}
\end{code}

Also note that JavaScript uses `console.log()` instead of `print()`

