Answer: To make your question clearer and easier for people to understand, you could provide some context as to why you need to know how to use switch statements in Java. But I'll give you my best guess on what you're asking and then I'll answer based on that.

It seems like you want to know how to do a switch statement in Java, which is similar to C#. In order to do a switch statement, you first define the variable or constant that you'll be switching over and then you start the switch block. Then you use the case blocks to match different values of the variable to perform different actions. Here's an example of how you would do that:

\begin{code}
String variable = "Hello"; // This variable holds the string "Hello"
switch(variable) {
    case "Hello":
        System.out.println("The variable holds the value Hello");
        break;
    case "World":
        System.out.println("The variable holds the value World");
        break;
    default:
        System.out.println("The variable does not hold the value Hello or World.");
        break;
}
\end{code}

This code above takes a String variable called `variable` and compares its value to each case statement. When one of them matches, it performs the associated action, which is printing out a message to the console in this case. You can also have a default statement which is executed if none of the cases matched.

You can find more information about switch statements in Java [here](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/switch.html).

