Comment: You need to escape the double quotes inside the string.

Answer: As mentioned by @StephenNewell you have to escape the double quotes as follows :

\begin{code}
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
int main() {
   cout << "Hello, world!" << endl;
}
\end{code}

So when you write this : \begin{code}
cout << "Hello, world!" << endl;
\end{code}, in fact the compiler reads this : \begin{code}
cout << Hello, world! << endl;
\end{code} which is wrong. So to indicate that we want to use the characters `"` literally inside the string, we use `\` before it like this: \begin{code}
cout << \"Hello, world!\" << endl;
\end{code}.

