Comment: In `Java` we use curly braces (`{}`) for _blocks_, e.g. `if (...) { ... }`.  This block starts after the _conditional expression_ and goes until its closing brace (or _closing bracket_).  There is no need to have empty `else` statements as in your example.  Thus, you could remove `else {}` from your `if` statement.

Answer: In java you cannot use if else without using brackets. It's mandatory to use brackets even if there is one line of code.

Example:

\begin{code}
int i = 1;
if(i == 1)
    System.out.println("test");
\end{code}

This will throw a compile time error but the same can be corrected by adding brackets.

\begin{code}
int i = 1;
if(i == 1){
    System.out.println("test");
}
\end{code}

You have to do the same in your code where you are using if else.

Answer: I would say that the most likely reason why the [online compiler](http://www.compileonline.com/compile_java_online.php) is showing that error message is because your code lacks some curly braces `{}`, e.g.:

\begin{code}
for (int i = 0; i < 4; ++i)
  if (i % 2 == 0)
    System.out.println("Even number!");
\end{code}

While technically correct, I would consider the above piece of code bad style since it can lead to errors if someone decides to add more lines inside the loop or the conditional.  For instance:

\begin{code}
for (int i = 0; i < 4; ++i)
  if (i % 2 == 0)
    System.out.println("Even number!");
    System.out.println("Something else...");
\end{code}

In the above code, the second `System.out.println(...)` will run regardless of whether `i` is odd or even.  To avoid such issues, I recommend using brackets when working with conditional statements.

