Answer: \strong{Solution}:

\begin{code}
print("# python")
\end{code}

The above code outputs `# python` which meets all conditions given in your question, specifically, that the code needs to be executable and that there should be no text printed to the console other than the code itself.

To address your comment about why my answer works, let's take a look at what `print()` does. From [the docs](https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#print):

\begin{blockquote}
Print objects to the text stream file, separated by sep and followed by
end. sep, end, file, flush and if are optional keyword-only arguments.
\end{blockquote}

So `print(something)` takes `something`, converts it to a string, and then prints it to the console. But what does `print()` return?

\begin{blockquote}
None.
\end{blockquote}

Yes, `print()` returns nothing, so if you run the code above in an interactive interpreter, you get:

\begin{code}
>>> print("# python")
# python
>>>
\end{code}

As you can see, `# python` gets printed to the console, but `None` also gets returned.

If you want to know more about why this works, I recommend reading up on how Python handles input/output, specifically [file objects](https://docs.python.org/3/glossary.html#term-file-object).

