\begin{code}
#include <stdio.h>
int main(void) {
    printf("Hello, world!\n");
}
\end{code}

And then to output the resulting Java code.

\section{What you need to do}

You should output the equivalent Java code. This means writing a complete Java program that prints out "Hello, world!" to the standard output.

It is important to note that the entire source code of the program must be written in the answer box when the submission is made.

Therefore, you should write:

\begin{code}
#include <stdio.h>
int main(void) {
    printf("Hello, world!\n");
}
\end{code}

as the content of the answer box, followed by a new line, and then `public class Main {}` on the next line. This will allow the code to compile as a valid Java program.

\section{How to write a Java program}

A simple example of a Java program would be:

\begin{code}
public class HelloWorld {
   public static void main(String[] args) {
      System.out.println("Hello World!");
   }
}
\end{code}

This program uses the `System.out.println` method to print out the string "Hello World!".

Note that every Java program needs a `main` function. This is the entry point for the program, and is where execution begins.

\section{Using `printf`}

As you have correctly observed, the original C code includes `printf`. However, this is not available in Java. Therefore, we need to use the `System.out.print` method instead.

For example, `printf("%d\n", 42);` becomes `System.out.println(42);`.

