Answer: Your post seems more like a "do my job" than a real question.
But if you really want some help, here are some translations between Java and C code :
\begin{itemize}
\item Java `String` -> C `char*` (string type)
\item Java `int` -> C `int`
\item Java `boolean` -> C `_Bool` or `bool` (if defined, see below)
\item Java `long` -> C `long int`
\item Java `float` -> C `float`
\item Java `double` -> C `double`
\item Java `byte` -> C `signed char`
\item Java `short` -> C `short`
\item Java `char` -> C `unsigned char`
\item Java `void` -> C `void`
\item Java `Object` -> C `void *`
\item Java `ArrayList` -> C `struct` + pointer manipulation (if you want something equivalent to ArrayList you should use linked lists in C)
\item Java `HashMap` -> C `struct` + pointer manipulation
\item Java `Interface` -> C `struct` + function pointers
\end{itemize}

In C, there is no native boolean type, but it is often emulated by using 0 (false) and 1 (true). The `_Bool` type was introduced in C99, so it's often used in modern code.

In C, dynamic memory allocation is done with `malloc()`/`free()`.

In your case, for example, you would have something like that :

\begin{code}
typedef struct Node {
    int val;
    struct Node *next;
} Node;

Node *head = NULL;

void addToTheEnd(int n) {
    // Allocate a new node with malloc()
    Node *node = malloc(sizeof(Node));

    // Initialize node members
    node->val = n;
    node->next = NULL;

    // Insert node at the end of the list
    Node *curr = head;
    while (curr && curr->next != NULL) {
        curr = curr->next;
    }
    curr->next = node;
}
\end{code}

That's just the beginning, you still have to implement things like deleting nodes, etc...

