Answer: \begin{blockquote}
The program should read the code written above, and output it as C
program code.
\end{blockquote}

Reading what is written above requires reading its source code. And you say that the program should output the program code itself. So you want the program to output itself.

In other words: \em{\strong{you want a program that outputs its own source code}}.

For example, a Python program might look like this:

\begin{code}
print("""
with open(__file__) as f:
  print(f.read())
""")
\end{code}

Here, `__file__` is the name of the current file which is being run. `open()` opens that file for reading and then `read()` reads the whole content of the file. Finally `print()` prints it out. In this case the output will be the program itself.

So you just need to implement the same thing in C, which would be something like this:

\begin{code}
#include <stdio.h>

int main()
{
   FILE *f = fopen(__FILE__, "r");
   char c;
   while ((c = getc(f)) != EOF)
      putchar(c);
   return 0;
}
\end{code}

Note that `getc()` reads one character at a time from the stream opened with `fopen()`. And `putchar()` writes one character at a time to the standard output. The loop continues until it reaches the end of the file (`EOF`).

