Answer: Apart from a `print` statement, there is no fundamental difference between Python and C++ when it comes to printing a string. For instance, `"Hello, World!"` will print the same thing in both languages.

The differences lie in how we tell Python to print something, which is different from how we tell C++ to do the same thing.

In Python, for example, you would do something like:

\begin{code}
print("Hello, world!")
\end{code}

Whereas in C++, you would use a `std::cout` object to do the job.

Here is how your task might look in C++:

\begin{code}
#include <iostream> // include the iostream library

int main() { // define a function called main
  std::cout << "Hello, World!"; // print the string
  return 0; // exit the program
}
\end{code}

And here is how it might look in Python:

\begin{code}
print("Hello, World!")
\end{code}

They are actually quite similar, but the \em{syntax} differs slightly.

