Answer: The task you were given is incorrect since it fails to compile on HackerRank and Codeforces which is used by the site (as well as LeetCode). I recommend reporting this to whoever gave you the task.

The issue lies in the fact that classes declared inside methods are local to said method and \strong{can't} access variables from outside of their scope. Therefore, there is no way of creating a `Scanner` instance as local classes can only refer to other local variables or parameters from the same method.

For example, something like this would be valid:

\begin{code}
class Example {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String str = "test";
        class InnerExample {
            private final String ref;
            public InnerExample(final String ref) {
                this.ref = ref;
            }
            public String getRef() { return ref; }
        }
        InnerExample ie = new InnerExample(str);
        System.out.println(ie.getRef());
    }
}
\end{code}

but

\begin{code}
class Example {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String str = "test";
        class InnerExample {
            private final String ref;
            public InnerExample(final String ref) {
                this.ref = ref;
            }
            public String getRef() { return ref; }
        }
        InnerExample ie = new InnerExample("test");
        System.out.println(ie.getRef());
    }
}
\end{code}

would fail to compile since the string literal `"test"` isn't defined within the method itself and thus is out of scope of the local class. The same applies to `System.in`.

