Answer: To execute Python code stored as a string within your Python program, you should be able to use [`exec()`](https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#exec).

You can pass it the string containing the code to execute:

\begin{code}
import random

random_num = random.randint(0, 1)

code = '''
if random_num == 0:
    print("The value was even!")
else:
    print("The value was odd.")'''

exec(code)
\end{code}

Note that, depending on your needs, you may want to use `exec()` within a function call, so that you can use [`locals()`](https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#locals) to store variables defined in the code. See [this answer](https://stackoverflow.com/a/938493/12578264) for more information.

Also note that `exec()` and `eval()` are considered security risks, since they allow you to execute arbitrary code from untrusted sources.

